You are an expert VS Code extension developer.

Your task is to build a complete VS Code extension in this workspace called:

"log-to-integration-test-generator"

The extension automatically generates integration tests from application logs.

Do the following actions in the workspace:
- Create folders
- Create files
- Write complete working code
- Ensure the extension compiles and runs

Tech stack
TypeScript
VS Code Extension API
Node.js runtime

Main Goal

The extension scans Spring Boot or Node.js application logs, extracts HTTP request/response interactions, reconstructs API flows, and generates integration tests using WireMock.

The generated tests and stubs should be written into the current project workspace.

-------------------------------------

STEP 1 – CREATE EXTENSION STRUCTURE

Create the following folder structure:

src/
  extension.ts
  commands/
      generateTests.ts
  parser/
      logParser.ts
  builder/
      interactionBuilder.ts
  ai/
      scenarioAgent.ts
  generator/
      wiremockGenerator.ts
      testGenerator.ts
  utils/
      fileWriter.ts
  models/
      HttpInteraction.ts
      TestScenario.ts

Also create:

package.json
tsconfig.json
README.md

-------------------------------------

STEP 2 – EXTENSION COMMAND

Add a command to the extension:

"Generate Integration Tests from Logs"

When executed the command should:

1 Ask the user to select a log file
2 Parse the log file
3 Extract HTTP interactions
4 Group interactions by traceId
5 Generate test scenarios
6 Generate WireMock stubs
7 Generate integration tests
8 Write files into the workspace

-------------------------------------

STEP 3 – DATA MODEL

Create model HttpInteraction with fields:

timestamp
traceId
method
url
requestBody
responseBody
status

Example:

{
 timestamp: string
 traceId: string
 method: string
 url: string
 requestBody: string
 responseBody: string
 status: number
}

-------------------------------------

STEP 4 – LOG PARSER

Implement logParser.ts.

It should read Spring Boot logs and detect:

HTTP_REQUEST
REQUEST_BODY
RESPONSE_STATUS
RESPONSE_BODY

Return a list of HttpInteraction objects.

-------------------------------------

STEP 5 – FLOW RECONSTRUCTION

Implement interactionBuilder.ts.

Responsibilities:

• Group interactions by traceId
• Sort interactions by timestamp
• Return flows

Each flow should represent a single integration test scenario.

-------------------------------------

STEP 6 – AI SCENARIO GENERATOR

Create scenarioAgent.ts.

Input:
List of HttpInteraction flows.

Responsibilities:

• identify API flows
• generate test scenario names
• generate WireMock stub definitions

Return object:

{
 scenarios:[
   {
     name:"",
     steps:[],
     stubs:[]
   }
 ]
}

For now mock the AI response.

Structure the code so it can later call an LLM API.

-------------------------------------

STEP 7 – WIREMOCK GENERATOR

Create wiremockGenerator.ts.

Generate stub JSON files like:

{
 "request":{
   "method":"POST",
   "url":"/payment"
 },
 "response":{
   "status":200,
   "jsonBody":{
     "status":"SUCCESS"
   }
 }
}

-------------------------------------

STEP 8 – TEST GENERATOR

Create testGenerator.ts.

Generate Spring Boot JUnit tests using WireMock.

Example structure:

@SpringBootTest
@AutoConfigureWireMock(port = 8089)

class PaymentFlowTest {

@Test
void testPaymentFlow(){

stubFor(post("/payment")
 .willReturn(okJson("{"status":"SUCCESS"}")));

}

}

-------------------------------------

STEP 9 – FILE OUTPUT

Generated files must be written to:

src/test/java/generated/
src/test/resources/wiremock/

Use Node filesystem API.

